instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Fast halo CME visible in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is believed to be backsided, with moving field lines and EUV wave visible in SDO AIA 171/193 at 2024-05-20T05:22Z. A filament eruption and C6.7 flare peaking at 2024-05-20T05:54Z from Active Region 3683 (approx. S24W65) occurred around the same time, but was determined not be the source of this fast halo CME due to location and timing.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME to the east. Its source could be 2024-05-20T18:36Z slow eruption in AR 3688, with dimming enlarging the coronal hole located to the south of this AR. The eruption is likely centered around (S25E35).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 coronagraph imagery. This event is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2024-05-23T20:53Z. The source is likely an eruption from N19E80 starting around 2024-05-23T22:15Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow CME to the west with the likely source an M-class flare and an associated minor eruption on/near the western limb seen starting around 2024-05-25T20:12Z in SDO AIA 304 imagery and as opening of field lines in AIA 193/171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Large partial halo, potential full halo CME with likely H-alpha emission seen with a bulk portion to the east in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is an X2.8 flare peaking at 2024-05-27T07:08Z from an unnumbered active region just beyond the SE limb (likely old AR3664 based on solar rotation calculations). The flare included the release of plasma/filament material best seen in SDO/AIA 304 and was followed by moving/opening field lines and EUV wave best seen in SDO/AIA 211 and GOES SUVI 284, as well as post-eruptive arcades best seen in SDO/AIA 193.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME in the SSW with no clear source; however there are a couple of potential coronal signatures - a slow possible ejecta seen in the SSW in AIA 171 starting after 2024-05-28T18Z and a faint movement of field lines far behind the limb in the SSW in AIA 171 at the same time as well. The CME is almost completely covered by the nighttime data gap in STEREO A coronagraph.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very faint partial halo CME in the NW seen only in difference imagery (SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2). No on-disk source have been found on the earth-facing disk, so it is likely backsided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Large, bright partial halo CME to east in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source of this CME is the X1.4 class flare from AR13697 with associated moving/opening field lines visible in SDO/AIA 193, 171, and GOES SUVI 284. Additionally, a thin filament ejecta was visible during the eruption as seen in GOES SUVI 304. Post-eruptive arcades followed the flare as seen in SDO/AIA 193 and 171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the S in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Overlaps with CME:2024-05-30T21:12Z. Source is opening field lines seen beyond the S limb starting around 2024-05-31T03:27Z as seen in SDO AIA 171. Opening field lines are also seen in GOES SUVI 284 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note:
A somewhat asymmetric full halo CME with two consecutive fronts seen best in SOHO LASCO C3 (but also in C2). With the exception of one (or two) early timestamps this event is covered by a large gap in STEREO A COR2. The indication of the backsided source of this halo in EUV imagery is possibly a faint and very fast movement of field lines that likely happens far behind the east limb seen starting 2024-06-01T18:39Z in AIA 171 in the ESE. 
The backsided analysis is supported by the location of a large backsided active region in helioseismology imagery from GONG - likely the former AR 13679 that was around lat/lon -8/-170 at the time of this event. In addition, STIX instrument on the Solar Orbiter detected a significant flare (equivalent of GOES X1)peaking at 2024-06-01T18:45Z.
Identifying the coronal signatures of this CME is complicated by an almost simultaneous X1.0 class flare from Active Region 13697 on the Earth-facing disk followed by a later M7.3 flare from the same front-sided Active Region. The front-sided flares are accompanied by relatively weak coronal signatures of eruption - dimming and post-eruptive arcades.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A CME to the SE with a complex uneven (pointy) front that comes on the heels of and overlaps with the preceding 2024-06-01T19:12Z halo CME (which was concluded to be backsided). The source of this, likely front-sided, CME could be the M7.3 flare from Active Region 3697 (S20E21) peaking at 2024-06-01T19:40Z and an associated eruption signified by post-eruptive arcades and a somewhat more eastern, not very deep, dimming centered very approximately around (S20E25). The front (e.g. the width) of this CME is not easy to determine because of the overlap with the preceding, likely backsided, halo and because the CME is partially obscured by the pylon in C3.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME has a brighter narrower bulk with a wider fainter shock seen to the east. No clear source found on the Earth-facing disk, however there are two potential sources: a very slow movement of field line beyond the east limb going on after 2024-06-04T20Z (which is far too early) or a similar slow movement of a field line beyond the sourtheast limb starting at 2024-06-05T01:20Z. Both movements are seen in AIA 193 and 335.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Large halo CME visible in STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. The source appears to be two back-to-back M-class flares from AR13697 with associated dimming signature to the north as well as nice filament ejecta to the west and north. Post-eruptive arcades are beginning to show in SDO/AIA 193. There is a large EUV wave associated with this event, as best seen in SDO/AIA 211.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright fast CME off the west limb seen in both coronagraphs. Its source is likely the series of two M-class flares from Active Region 3697 (S18W91). Ejecta in AIA 131 was seen starting at 2024-06-10T10:00Z and the opening of field lines starts at 10:20Z however the major opening of field lines is seen at 10:45Z indicating that the major contribution might have come from the M5.3 flare peaking at 2024-06-10T10:58Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A CME with a dimpled bulk front (and a much wider fainter shock front) which is very closely following the 2024-06-10T11:00Z CME. This CME is likely associated with the X1.5 class flare from Active Region 3697 that follows the M5.3 class flare. Coronal signatures include minor post-eruptive arcades on west limb and faint minor dimming seen in AIA 193 starting after 2024-06-10T12:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Wide CME seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, not in STEREO COR2A due to a lengthy data gap over this period. The source is an occulted M9.5 flare from AR 3697 (estimated around the limb ~S18W96 at the time) which peaked at 2024-06-10T18:40Z, best observed in SDO AIA 131. Also observed as field line movement and an EUV wave in SDO AIA 171/193/211 starting around 2024-06-11T17:54Z, with post-eruptive arcades forming after the flare peak.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Wide filament eruption seen to the SW in all coronagraphs. Source is a filament eruption from the far-side of the disk, observed best as the filament material itself in SDO AIA 304 launching around 2024-06-10T22:30Z from around S30-S40. The filament material appears to be closer to the limb, but is accompanied by a wider far-sided field line movement in SDO AIA 171/193/211 that appears further around the limb. This is corroborated by the fit in swpc_cat between SOHO and STEREO coronagraphs not working unless longitudes >W130 were used. It appears that two fronts are traveling together from this front--perhaps the filament and field line movements--and are thus measured as one for this analysis.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Backsided partial halo CME first seen in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2024-06-11T23:12Z after a data gap; it is first seen in STEREO A COR2 coronagraph at 2024-06-12T00:38Z, after a large data gap which starts at 2024-06-11T12:53Z. Coronal signatures of this event include a backsided EUV wave seen as a fast opening/movement of field lines behind the west limb and a significant restructuring of magnetic field behind the limb seen in SDO AIA 171, 193, GOES SUVI 195, 171 and 304 imagery starting at 2024-06-11T22:39Z and in EUVI STEREO A 195 imagery after the data gap. The likely source of the CME is the old Active Region 3697 which is at S18W112 at the time of eruption.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Large bright CME seen to the west in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. There is a data gap in STEREO A imagery for this event from 2024-06-12T12:53Z to 2024-06-13T00:38Z. Moving/opening field lines best seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2024-06-12T15:00Z beyond the western limb. Moving/opening field lines are also visible in SDO/AIA 171 starting around 2024-06-12T15:20Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible as a halo in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery and is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. The source is likely far-sided. An eruption and subsequent M1.2 flare from Active Region 13711 (S12E12) is visible starting around 2024-06-12T22:40Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, and 304 imagery. However, this eruption appears to deflect towards the west and the source location does not provide an accurate measurement for this CME. Therefore, this event is more likely to be far-sided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the west/northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source may be related to a faint eruption visible beyond the western limb in SDO AIA 131 and 304 imagery, with subsequent field line movement seen in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery, starting around 2024-06-13T03:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures visible on the Earth-facing disk at this time.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the west/northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery for a few frames preceding a data gap from 2024-06-13T15:53 to 17:53Z. The source may be related to faint field line movement visible beyond the northwest limb in SDO AIA 171 imagery starting around 2024-06-13T15:15Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the south in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is a filament eruption with liftoff starting around 2024-06-15T11:10Z in SDO AIA 304. The eruption is also visible with moving/opening field lines in SDO AIA 171/193/335, brightening and post-eruptive arcades visible in SDO AIA 335, and dimming and post-eruptive arcades in SDO AIA 193. The eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUV 195 and 304. The filament eruption may deflect towards the west after liftoff as seen in GOES SUVI 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Wide CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is widely opening field lines beyond the S/SE limb as seen in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284 starting at 2024-06-17T08:00Z. There is a fainter full halo portion of this CME which may be the shock portion.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is not visible on the disk in available EUV imagery, but there is possibly some field line movement visible between frames 10:35Z and 10:55Z in STEREO A EUVI 195 and 304 imagery at a fairly high northern latitude and beyond the W limb as seen from STEREO A.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: First of two paired CMEs seen to the W in all coronagraphs (this one is more northern), following an M1.1 flare which peaked at 2024-06-19T06:38Z from AR 3711 seen in SDO AIA 131 with some field line movement seen in SDO AIA 171/193/211 at this time. Two fronts appear to travel out from this eruption, both only fitting near this source but fitting far enough apart in lat/lon to warrant two separate entries (see CME 2024-06-19T07:00Z). Interestingly, this eruption did not look too impressive in SDO AIA imagery, but far-sided fits of the fronts proved far worse than using this source longitude, so higher confidence is granted in this source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible as a partial halo to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is a large eruption visible near/slightly beyond the eastern limb in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery starting around 2024-06-21T23:37Z. A wide opening of field lines is visible near the eastern limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery at this time as well. Based on GONG far-sided imagery, it is possible this eruption occurred from former Active Region 13697. This region would have been located around longitude -110 to -115 degrees at the time of this event based on the rate of solar rotation.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME with a hazy leading edge seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is an eruption at S20W62, at AR 3719, starting at 2024-06-29T03:09Z as seen in SDO AIA 304. Ejecta can be seen throughout the eruption in SDO AIA 304 and 171. Opening field lines are seen in SDO AIA 171 and 193. Eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUVI 193 and 304. The CME:2024-06-29T04:00Z overlaps with this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Wide CME visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and S/SW in STEREO A COR2. The source is a large filament eruption spanning from S30E10 to S20W40. Liftoff seen starting at about 2024-06-29T15:09Z in SDO AIA 304. Dimming and post-eruptive arcades are visible in SDO AIA 193. Opening field lines are visible in SDO AIA 171. The eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUV 195/304 after a data gap from 2024-06-29T13:05Z to 2024-06-29T17:25Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Complex shaped asymmetrical halo first seen in SOHO to the northeast but then encompassing the whole sun. It has a clear, narrower bulk to the northeast and a more wider farsided shock. It looks like a full halo in STEREO A after a long data gap which ends at 2024-07-11T23:38Z, with only one COR2 image showing the whole CME front before the CME exits the field-of-view of the coronagraph. No source on the earth-facing side has been found in EUV imagery, so it is clearly a backsided event. One possible indication of the farsided eruption may be a slight fast movement of field lines in the northeast seen in GOES SUVI 284 at ~2024-07-10T21:25Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very faint but fast partial halo CME covered by a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 and first seen in C3. The source (initially very hard to identify) was found in GOES SUVI 304 as a long but faint filament erupting (likely) behind the ENE limb starting at 2024-07-12T22:50Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow fast jet with a brighter narrower bulk and a fainter also narrow shock. One potential source - unspecified flaring and rising loops on the NE limb simultaneous with the flare from Active Region 3738 in the west - is not supported by the analysis using the best fit of this narrow CME with two coronagraphs, which indicates an off-the-limb location.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is a prominence eruption visible off the NE limb in SDO AIA 304 with liftoff starting around 2024-07-16T00:08Z. Opening field lines are visible in SDO AIA 171/193/335, brightening best seen in SDO AIA 94/131/193, and post-eruptive arcades are best seen in SDO AIA 94/171/193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is unclear, and may be beyond the limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. This was determined to likely be separate from CME: 2024-07-16T23:12Z. There were multiple source candidates for this CME, with the best candidate being an eruption with moving/opening field lines from AR 13751 around 2024-07-16T20:27Z as seen in SDO AIA 171/193.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Filament eruption seen to the SE in all coronagraphs, but only a few frames of STEREO COR2A due to a data gap over this period from 2024-07-17T13:38Z-T23:38Z with a rogue image at T20:23Z that assisted with triangulation. The source is a filament sitting on or just inside the SE limb around S32E90, which began to erupt around 2024-07-17T17:00Z. The start of this eruption was observed in SDO AIA 131/171/193/211/304 but cut short due to a shutter maneuver, GOES SUVI 171/195/284/304 caught the entire, spectacular filament eruption.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible as a far-sided halo in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery, with the bulk of the material directed towards the northwest. The source is likely far-sided as faint field line movement is visible beyond the northwest limb in SDO AIA 171, 193 and GOES SUVI 171, 193, 284 imagery starting around 2024-07-22T23:30Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright CME seen to the E in all coronagraphs. The source is an M2.4 flare from an unnumbered region on the SE limb around S10E77, which peaked at 2024-07-23T14:28Z, best seen in SDO AIA 131. Also observed starting around 2024-07-23T13:34Z as rapid field line opening with an EUV wave, followed by post-eruptive arcades, in SDO AIA 171/193/211 with surface brightening in SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Messy halo CME seen with a bulk portion to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. Solar Orbiter detected an estimated X7 class flare on the far side peaking at  2024-07-24T23:25Z that may be the source of this halo feature.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Partial halo CME with bulk seen to the E/NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. This CME has a bright core with a portion trailing out in a spiral formation from the main bulk (almost appears as a partial Fibonacci spiral in C3 imagery). The source is likely far-sided based on moving/opening field lines visible in GOES SUVI 284 along the E/NE limb starting around 2024-07-27T04:38Z. Solar Orbiter detected an estimated X1 class flare on the far-side peaking at 2024-07-27T04:30Z that may be the source of this partial halo.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Asymmetric halo CME visible towards the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and towards the NE in STEREO A COR2. The source is an M3.1 flare from AR 3762 with dimming/EUV wave towards the N/NW starting at 2024-07-27T05:42Z best seen in GOES SUVI 195 and 284 (SDO/AIA has an eclipse shortly after the event starts). The eruption is also visible south of disk center as seen in available EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Full halo CME visible in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and towards the east in STEREO A COR2. The source is likely the M9.9 flare peaking at 2024-07-28T01:57Z from AR 3766 and/or the M7.8 flare directly preceding it from the same region. Dimming and EUV wave visible in SDO AIA 193 and 335 and GOES SUVI 284, post-eruptive arcades visible in SDO AIA 131/171/193. The eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and some frames in STEREO A COR2 (small data gaps with limited imagery for this event). The source is a flare from an unnumbered active region along the SE limb as seen in SDO/AIA 131 peaking around 2024-07-29T14:46Z. The exact flare class is unknown due to the simultaneous flaring from another active region, together the two regions reached an M4.2 class flare.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. There is a data gap in STEREO A COR2 for this event. The source is an M6.4 class flare from an unnumbered AR near S25E85.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Fast CME seen mainly in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, partially observed in STEREO COR2A due to a data gap spanning 2024-07-30T13:09Z-T22:38Z where it only catches some material leaving the FOV and not of the front itself. The source for this CME is an M9.4 flare from AR 3772 which peaked at 2024-07-30T19:38Z, observed best in SDO AIA 131 but also notably in SDO AIA 193! Also observed as brightening in SDO AIA 304, slight dimming in SDO AIA 193, and field line movement deflected southward in SDO AIA 171/193/211 and GOES SUVI 171/193/284. This deflection appears to push the CME out of the ecliptic despite the source located at S25 latitude.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is likely the M7.7 flare peaking at 2024-07-31T06:46Z from AR 3768 (approx. S15W60). EUV wave and opening field lines are seen in GOES SUVI 195 and 284. Post-eruptive loops are best seen in GOES SUVI 171 and 195. The eruption is not visible in SDO AIA imagery due to an eclipse. The eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUV imagery. Overlaps in the field of view with CME: 2024-07-31T08:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery and STEREO A COR2 prior to a data gap starting at 2024-07-31T13:53Z. The source is likely an eruption and M6.0 flare from Active Region 13772 (S25E55) starting around 2024-07-31T12:50Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. An opening of field lines is visible over the southeast limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery at this time as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible as a partial halo to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery, and is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. The source is likely an M5.3 flare and eruption from AR 3768 (S15W73) starting around 2024-07-31T18:05Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. A wide opening of field lines is visible at this time in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery which appear to deflect north of the eruption site.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible as a partial halo to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 coronagraph imagery. The source is an M8.2 flare and eruption from Active Region 13768 (S15W80) starting around 2024-08-01T07:00Z as seen in GOES SUVI 131, 171, 195, 284, 304 imagery. A wide opening of field lines is visible in GOES SUVI 171, 195, and 284 imagery at this time as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely an eruption and M4.1 flare from Active Region 13772 (S25E41) starting around 2024-08-01T11:20Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Wide, bright CME to the W in all coronagraphs. Source is an eruption from AR 3768 beginning around 2024-08-02T04:27Z, observed as wide field line movement, EUV wave, and a following post-eruptive arcade in SDO AIA 171/193/211/304 and GOES SUVI 171/195/284. Accompanied by a long-duration M7.4 flare which peaked at 2024-08-02T04:55Z, observed best in SDO AIA 131.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the south/southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright and wide CME where the source is an X1.7 class flare from just behind the west limb, possibly from Active Region 13795 which rotated behind the limb on the previous day. The flare is seen close to the west limb in STEREO EUVI A imagery. The associated eruption is seen right after the flare in SDO AIA/SUVI 304 and is marked by the wide opening of field lines and by a massive restructuring of magnetic field on or behind the limb, as seen in SDO AIA 193/171 and in GOES SUVI 193/284 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. The CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 in real-time due to a data gap starting at 2024-08-07T14:09Z. Eruption with M4.5 flare from AR 3774 (approx. S10W22), field line movement, and possible faint EUV wave visible in SDO AIA 193. Opening field lines are best seen in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284. The eruption is also visible from the point of view of STEREO A EUV 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Partial halo CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is an M4.5 flare peaking at 2024-08-09T21:23Z from AR 3774 (approx. S05W40). Eruption with rising/opening field lines and dimming are best seen in SDO AIA 193, GOES 284, and STEREO A EUV 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Jet-like CME first seen to the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-14T03:48Z as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source appears to be a small filament eruption located at approx. S30W100 beginning around 2024-08-14T01:50Z exhibiting a more Southern deflection as seen in SDO AIA and STEREO A EUVI 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint jet-like CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-14T09:12Z as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. There is no clear source seen on the Earth facing disk, however some faint field line opening can be seen in SDO AIA 193, leading to a likely far sided source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Extremely faint and narrow CME seen to the E in STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C2. Extremely faint in C3. Source is opening field lines on the E limb seen in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2024-08-14T23:30Z, from AR 13790 (S10E80).
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is faintly visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and a few frames within a data gap of STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source appears to be filament ejecta visible along the western limb starting around 2024-08-17T18:53Z best seen in SDO/AIA and GOES SUVI 304. There are moving/opening field lines also visible starting around 2024-08-17T19:00Z in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the south in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is not clear. There is filament ejecta visible to the S/SE starting around 2024-08-20T16:45Z which isn't best for timing, however with limited stereoscopic viewpoints of the solar disk, it's possible there was an earlier eruption and the filament ejecta was seen later, this is very speculative though.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint, fast CME seen to the E in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO COR2A is not in a data gap but does not observe this CME, likely due to the faint nature. The source for this CME is uncertain, and may only be observed in SDO AIA 171 around 2024-08-20T07:12Z as some dimming in the field lines over the SE limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: A very complex CME with a wider fainter partial halo component (possible shock) and a narrower complex-shaped brighter portion that potentially has several lobes. No corresponding source has been found on the Earth-facing disk. There was an equivalent of an M3 class flare seen by STIX instrument on the Solar Orbiter peaking at 2024-08-22T14:37Z with the very approximate longitude of 180, which could be the far sided possible source of this CME.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Fast, faint CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. The source appears to be jet-like filament eruptions on or around the west limb, best observed in GOES SUVI 284 at 2024-08-23T14:56Z, with a second one at 16:20Z less likely due to timing.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME seen to the W in all coronagraphs, but best in STEREO COR2A. The source is not completely clear, and may be a part of some field line movement on/around the west limb in SDO AIA 171 beginning as early as 2024-08-30T18:22Z. This CME is notably extremely faint in SOHO imagery.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright CME seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is a large eruption on the SE limb seen as brightening starting at 2024-09-01T11:06Z in SDO AIA 131, ejection of material at 11:18Z in SDO AIA 304, rapidly opening field lines seen beyond the limb starting at 11:30Z in SDO AIA 171/193. Slow rise and eventual ejection of two overlapping flux rope loops from the southeast limb seen starting as early as 2024-09-01T08:08Z in GOES SUVI 304. Long-duration M5.5 flare associated with brightening from post-eruptive arcades that spanned from S20-S30, as seen in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI imagery.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME seen to the S/SE following the path of the 2024-09-01T12:23Z CME in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. No clear visible source in SDO/AIA or GOES/SUVI imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright full asymmetric halo CME in SOHO and a partial northwestern halo in STEREO A, with a fainter but distinct shock front in addition to a very bright bulk. Its source is likely farsided and is indicated by the faint but very wide opening of field lines/restructuring of magnetic field far behind the northwest (extending faintly to southwest) limb, as seen in SDO 193/171 starting at 2024-09-03T08:18Z, also seen in STA EUV 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fairly symmetrical halo CME with brighter portions to the NW in SOHO and NE in STEREO A, first seen around 2024-09-05T07:24Z in SOHO C2. The eruption is very likely on the far-side relative to the Earth-facing solar disk as evidenced by flickering field lines seen best in SDO AIA 193/171 and GOES SUVI 284 far off the northwest and southwest limbs seen around 2024-09-05T07:15Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME seen to the W in C2 and STEREO A COR2. Not visible in C3. Leading edge appears brighter in STEREO A COR2 than in SOHO LASCO. Source is opening field lines seen at 2023-09-08T09:15Z just beyond the limb as seen in STEREO-A EUVI 304 and 195 imagery, at about S10.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Large, bright lightbulb CME to the west in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source appears to be a long duration M1.0 flare from AR13806 (~S05W89). Moving/opening field lines are visible in SDO/AIA 171 and 193 starting around 2024-09-09T00:24Z along the western limb with post-eruptive arcades visible starting around 2024-09-09T02:24Z. The eruption is also visible in GOES SUVI before an eclipse occurs and in STEREO A EUVI 304 and 195 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Large bright halo CME with bulk to the NE in STEREO A COR2 and following a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. The source appears to be beyond the eastern limb in SDO/AIA 193 and 211 starting around 2024-09-09T05:00Z with a visible rising loop and clear moving/opening field lines. There is a dimming/reconstruction/EUV wave in the coronal material along the limb. Possible filament material is visible in SDO/AIA 171 and 304 briefly around 2024-09-09T05:10Z. Moving field lines are briefly visible in GOES SUVI 284 before an eclipse occurs.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Wide CME first seen in the South by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-10T20:12Z as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a far sided filament eruption and resulting field line movement seen off the South limb in GOES SUVI 171, 195, 284 and 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint yet fast CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-11T16:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. There is no STEREO A COR2 data available for this event due to a data gap from 2024-09-11T14:38Z to 2024-09-11T22:23Z. The source of this event is an M1.8 class flare peaking at 2024-09-11T15:30Z and a subsequent fast eruption of material seen along the Eastern limb (approx. S20E90). The flare is seen clearly in SDO AIA 131, along with material seen leaving the disk in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304. Field line movement can be seen in SDO AIA 171 and 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Partial halo CME seen to the southeast in SOHO C2/C3 and not yet observed in STEREO A due to a data gap. Associated with a powerful X4.5-class solar flare from AR3825 (S18E55) and subsequent strong eruption, characterized by intense brightening in SDO 131 and fast ejecta seen best in GOES SUVI 284 as well as a large, fast EUV wave associated with the eruption traversing back towards the northwest seen best in SDO AIA 171/193 that covers approximately half the solar disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME seen to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and after a data gap in STEREO A COR2 from 2024-09-14T17:38Z to 2024-09-14T22:38Z. The source is not seen in EUV imagery. The CME follows directly after CME: 2024-09-14T19:36Z in the coronagraphs.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-18T05:48Z as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. There is no clear source seen on the disk for this event, however some minor field line opening can be seen off of the SW limb in SDO AIA 171, 193 and GOES SUVI 284, suggesting a far sided eruption. This CME does not have a distinct leading edge and significantly widens as it progresses.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fuzzy CME seen to the NW in all coronagraphs. The source for this CME is uncertain and unobserved in EUV imagery, but clearly lies far-sided via triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A in swpc_cat.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-22T21:36Z. The source of this event is an M3.7 flare and filament eruption from S23E65 beginning at 2024-09-22T21:12Z. This flare is seen clearly in SDO AIA 94 and 131, and the filament material is seen best in SDO AIA 304. Field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, and GOES SUVI 284 along with post eruptive arcades visible in SDO AIA 94 and 131. This filament appears to deflect towards the SW as it progresses as seen in GOES SUVI 304. A faint EUV wave seen in SDO AIA 193 also appears to expand more to the west.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow, fast eruption seen to the southwest in SOHO C2 and due west in STEREO A COR2, accompanied by a much wider, faint shock seen to the northwest in SOHO C2/C3. Appears to be associated with an eruption near AR3834 (S15W42) seen in SDO AIA 193/171 around 2024-09-29T05:15Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very asymmetric CME with two (or more) consecutive fronts (or possibly two overlapping CMEs). The source is a relatively minor eruption centered east of AR3834 - around ~S15W55 - with a very fast ejecta and dimming, as seen in the SW in AIA 193/304/171 at 15:57Z. STEREO A coronagraph imagery is available but very sporadic and poor quality b/c of the campaign mode.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Developing CME with bulk seen predominantly to the southeast in early frames with a very faint, oval-shaped/asymmetric halo shock portion, associated with an X7.1-class flare and associated eruption from AR3842 (S17E18). Coronal signatures include an EUV wave and large-scale dimming in SDO AIA 171/193 with magnetic field line movement off the southern and southeast limbs and dimming of footpoints bridging the Active Region 3842 (S17E18) in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Full halo CME observed in SOHO LASCO, and full halo directed slightly more eastward in STEREO COR2A. The source is an X9.0 flare from AR 3842 observed in many wavelengths but mainly SDO AIA 131, starting at 2024-10-03T12:08Z and peaking at T12:18Z. Also observed as an EUV wave and dimming in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284, with surface brightening in SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is faintly visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and to the south in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source appears to be two eruptions in close proximity to each other in the SW quadrant of the Earth-facing disk. A dimming region possibly associated with a faint filament eruption is visible in SDO/AIA 193 starting around 2024-10-04T02:00Z in the SW near ARs 13842, 13839, and 13844 followed by moving/opening field lines visible in SDO/AIA 171 starting around 2024-10-04T03:00Z in the SW below ARs 13844, 13843, and 13836. The moving/opening field lines are largely visible heading to the west while the dimming appears to have some southern directionality. A third separate eruption from AR 13842 (an M4.0 flare) is likely associated with an overlapping CME feature. There is some uncertainty with this analysis due to the multiple eruptions in close proximity and timing to when the CME is first visible in coronagraph imagery. Both SOHO and STEREO A coronagraphs have data gaps during this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-04T13:25Z as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is an eruption from the vicinity of AR 3844 (S15W37) beginning at approximately 04/12:30Z, although the CME itself appears to exhibit Southern deflection. Field line opening can be seen clearly in SDO AIA 171 along with post eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 131.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A wide CME directly north in STEREO A coronagraph and a bit towards NNE in SOHO. There is a wider shock and a narrower brighter bulk. The shock looks like an asymmetric halo with additional part seen to the west in COR2A. There was no source found on the Earth-facing disk so the CME is likely backsided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A faint narrow outflow towards northwest. No clear source have been found for it, although there is a lot of activity in the western part of the disk today. The CME is not seen in STEREO imagery because of a large data gap.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery, and is only visible in STEREO A COR2 after the leading edge is out of the field of view due to a data gap from 2024-10-08T03:38Z to 09:23Z. The source is a large filament eruption centered near S25W30 which begins to erupt, deflecting southward, around 2024-10-08T05:20Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. A subsequent opening of field lines is visible over the southwest limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery at the time of the eruption, and post-eruptive arcades begin to form around 06:30Z in SDO AIA131, 171, and 193 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Relatively narrow CME first seen in the East initially by STEREO A COR2, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 in later frames. This event gets quickly overtaken by the X1.8-flare-associated halo 2024-10-09T02:12Z CME. The source of this event is possibly a more minor flare sympathetic to the X flare happening at the same time in Active Region 3853 (N20E63) with post-eruptive arcades or more minor opening field lines and slight dimming seen in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284 originating from the vicinity of AR 3852 (S14E53). This more minor flare is not measurable since it coincides with the more intense flare.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright, fast and complex-shaped full halo CME associated with the X1.8 class flare from the Active Region 13848 (N13W08). The CME has two lobes or fronts: the more western, slightly earlier one, and the more central on to the northeast. The flare is associated with the significant eruption marked by an EUV wave, a large area of deep dimming and by bright post-eruptive arcades. There also  seems to be a second eruption - the initially slowly developing eruption of a very large filament spanning from N20W15 to N15W55, to the northwest of the Active Region 3848, which starts prior to the X flare (~2024-10-08T22:19Z). This earlier eruption may be responsible for the more western lobe or front of this CME (which could possibly be a separate CME). The X-class flare could be potentially be responsible for the more central, northeastern lobe/front of this complex event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A clear, more western loop especially well seen in SOHO C2 (starting at 2024-10-09T02:12Z) and overlapping with a more central front associated with the Xclass flare. The start time was set to 02:23Z to distinguish it from the more central CME. The source of this more western front is likely the initially slowly developing eruption of a very large filament spanning from N20W15 to N15W55 to the northwest of Active Region 3848 which started prior to the X flare (~2024-10-08T22:19Z). This earlier eruption may be responsible for the more western lobe/front, while the flare could be responsible for the more central, northeastern front of this complex CME.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the W/NW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and a few frames of STEREO A COR2 after a data gap in STEREO A COR2 lasting from 2024-10-09T13:53Z to 2024-10-09T18:53Z. This CME is associated with the X1.4 flare from AR 13842 (S10W85) close to the SW limb. There is a narrow stream of ejecta visible in GOES SUVI 304 sourced from AR 13842 but deflected to the north and off the limb. In GOES SUVI 284, wide and fast opening field lines and departure of plasma from the W limb is visible. Very limited SDO AIA imagery for this event due to a shutter maneuver.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Halo CME first seen by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2024-10-01-T09:53Z, as well as in the East by SOHO LASCO C2/C3. There is no clear source seen for this event, however spacecraft triangulation (currently a 26 degree separation) reveals that this event likely originated from the far side, so a source eruption would be too far beyond the West limb to be visible.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-11T12:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament eruption seen on or just beyond the NW limb (footpoint at approx. S02W90 exhibiting Northern deflection) beginning at approx. 11/12:08Z as seen in SDO AIA, GOES SUVI and STEREO A EUVI 304. Opening field lines are also visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Large messy CME to the W/NW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. There is no clear source for this CME. There may be a wide shock feature associated with this CME that is faintly visible in white light and difference imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. This CME slightly overlaps the CME at 2024-10-13T01:36Z. There is no clear source for this CME.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-14T09:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a very long filament eruption beginning at approx. 14/08:00Z centered at approx. S30W70 as seen in SDO AIA, GOES SUVI and STEREO A EUVI 304. Opening field lines are visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211, GOES SUVI 284 and STEREO A EUVI 195 along with post eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 131, 193 and STEREO A EUVI 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible as a far-sided halo, primarily directed towards the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery and northwest in STEREO A COR2. The source is likely far-sided as an opening of field lines is visible beyond the northeast limb starting around 2024-10-16T22:10Z in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery. The source may originate from former Active Region 13841, which was located around longitude -163 at the time of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the E/NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source appears to be an eruption from AR 3863 starting around 2024-10-19T09:00Z in SDO/AIA 304/171/211/94. Moving/opening field lines are visible in the SE of SDO/AIA 171, however it is not clear if these moving/opening field lines are associated with this eruption or another eruption that may be associated with the CME first seen in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2024-10-19T09:48Z to the SE.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Source is one of several instances of narrowly opening field lines and ejecta from either on or just beyond the E limb at latitude N00, but with northern deflection. Instances start as early as 2024-10-22T03:41Z (very diffuse outflow associated with that instance). There is a clearer instance of ejecta seen at 2024-10-22T07:30Z, which may possibly be the source for this CME, though the timing is rather early. It's also possible the source for this particular front is sourced from even further beyond the limb than we can see in UV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Partial halo CME visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is an X3.3 flare starting at 2024-10-24T03:30Z from AR 3869 (approx. S17E68). Brightening and post eruptive arcades are observed in SDO AIA 131/171/193/335, EUV wave seen in SDO AIA 193, and opening field lines are best seen in SDO AIA 171/193. The eruption is also seen from STEREO A EUV 195/304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow jet CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 running difference imagery beginning at 2024-10-24T14:36Z. In real-time, there was no SOHO LASCO C2/C3 white light imagery available due to a data outage beginning at 2024-10-24T12:48Z that resolved and backfilled on 2024-10-25. There is also no STEREO A COR2 imagery available due to a data gap from 13:23Z to 23:38Z. The source of this event is a small eruption along the East limb (approx. S02E85) as seen in SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow jet CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 running difference imagery beginning at 2024-10-24T16:12Z. In real-time, there was no SOHO LASCO C2/C3 white light imagery available due to a data outage beginning at 2024-10-24T12:48Z that resolved and backfilled on 2024-10-25. There is also no STEREO A COR2 imagery available due to a data gap from 13:23Z to 23:38Z. The source of this CME is some faint field line movement seen beyond the East limb in SDO AIA 171. This source seems to be obscured by the brightening of an active region which has just rotated onto the disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible as a partial halo directed towards the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is an eruption which is associated with an M9.5 flare from Active Region 13873 (S14E56) and X1.8 flare from Active Region 13873 (S16E60) starting around 2024-10-26T06:30Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. A wide opening of field lines is visible over the southeast limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193, with post eruptive arcades visible in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 starting around 07:50Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This event is visible for one frame in STEREO A COR2 imagery to the southwest, prior to a data gap from 2024-10-29T13:23Z to 23:23Z. In SOHO LASCO C3 this event is visible as a partial halo directed towards the southwest, but the CME is only observable for a few frames before it exits the field of view. The source is a large filament eruption spanning about S37W25 to S15W90, likely extending beyond the western limb, which begins to erupt around 2024-10-29T12:40Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. Dimming is visible around the eruption site in SDO AIA 193 around 14:15Z, and post eruptive arcades begin to form around 17:15Z in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen to the SSW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-10-30T04:12Z. Also seen to the SSW in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is likely an area of broad and slow moving field lines on the SSW limb in GOES SUVI 284 starting as early as 2024-10-30T02:30Z, but with a more defined rising loop seen at 2024-10-30T03:25Z. There is also a localized area of dimming best seen in SDO AIA 193 in the SW quadrant of the Earth-facing disk starting about 2024-10-30T03:28Z. It is difficult to distinguish the sources of CME: 2024-10-30T04:12Z and the slower moving CME: 2024-10-30T05:00Z that is slightly farther to the S.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Partial halo CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2. The CME is visible in SOHO LASCO C3 after a data gap from 2024-11-04T02:18Z to 2024-11-04T05:43Z. The CME is associated with an M3.8 flare from AR 3883 (approximately S04E42) peaking at 2024-11-04T01:40Z. The eruption can be seen in all wavelengths of SDO AIA imagery, with brightening best seen in SDO AIA 131, dimming and EUV wave best seen in SDO AIA 193, and opening field lines best seen in SDO AIA 171. The eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in STEREO A COR2 imagery and SOHO LASCO C2/C3 following a data gap lasting from 2024-11-07T02:12Z to 07:36Z. The source is a filament eruption visible near the southwest limb (~S30W70) starting around 2024-11-07T05:15Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. A subsequent opening of field lines is visible over the southwest limb at this time in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery, and post-eruptive arcades begin to form around 2024-11-07T07:00Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen in the West by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2024-11-10T23:09Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 in later frames. The source of this event is a C8.4 class flare from AR 3881 (S09W98) beginning at 10/22:31Z. This flare is visible in SDO AIA 94, 131,and STEREO A EUVI 195, along with field line opening seen in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211, and GOES SUVI 304, as well as post eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 131 and STEREO A EUVI 195.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: A very faint but fast and relatively narrow CME with the fuzzy front that is only somewhat clearly seen in STEREO A COR2 running difference imagery. Its source is likely a relatively minor filament eruption seen starting around 2024-11-11T00:10Z, as seen in SDO AIA 304/193, GOES SUVI 304/195/284 and STEREO A EUVI 195. The filament is centered at ~N20E25 and stretches from N27E40 to N17E17. Coronal signatures of this CME include an ejecta seen erupting in SDO AIA 304 and a dimming and post-eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 193/195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-11-12T13:36Z. CME also visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C3. The source of this CME is a filament eruption on the NW limb. The footpoints are centered at about N14 and N30. The filament is best seen in SDO AIA 304 and can be seen rising off the disk starting about 2024-11-12T11:51Z. The filament "snaps" at about 2024-11-12T13:10Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-11-17T11:00Z as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is field line opening and brightening from a currently unnumbered Active Region along the NE limb (approx. N25E90) at approx. 17/09:45Z. This field line movement can be seen in SDO AIA 171, along with post eruptive arcades in SDO AIA 131.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright and fast partial halo to the northwest, with bulk and (fainter) shock fronts, associated with the fast backsided eruption marked by an EUV wave and fast opening of field lines behind the NW limb seen around 2024-11-21T18Z. The source is backsided, based on the coronal signatures and might be Active Region 3889 which would be at the longitude 115 to 120 degrees at the moment.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is faintly visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source appears to be an eruption in the NE between N25E35 to N35E50 associated with moving/opening field lines in SDO/AIA 171, dimming in SDO/AIA 193, and brightening in SDO/AIA 131 between 21:00Z and 22:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the NW in all coronagraphs. The source for this CME is uncertain with no visible source in SDO AIA, GOES SUVI, or STEREO A EUVI. The CME is less visible in SOHO LASCO C2, becoming more distinct in LASCO C3 and STEREO COR2A.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first visible in the West by STEREO A COR 2 beginning at 2024-11-22T09:38Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 in later frames. There is no clear source seen for this CME, and the leading edge fades quickly in SOHO LASCO C2/C3.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the west/southwest in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. There is a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery for this CME. The front appears to be faint with a brighter core and possible h-alpha emission visible in C2 imagery. The source appears to be a filament eruption starting around 17Z beyond the SW limb in SDO/AIA 304. Associated moving/opening field lines are visible in SDO/AIA 171 and 193 as well as in GOES SUVI 284 imagery
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the south in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and possibly to the SE in STEREO A COR2 imagery following a data gap. The CME is likely associated with the M1.9 flare from AR 13091 as seen from SDO/AIA 131 and associated dimming in SDO/AIA 193 starting around 20:33Z. The dimming and associated EUV wave is seen moving out in all directions, most notably seen to the north, east, and south of the source location. This CME event overlaps with CMEs visible to the southwest which began around 2024-11-25T18:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to the faintness of the CME. Source is a C3.5 flare from S20W72 (no AR) with peak time 2024-11-27T02:28Z and a narrow ribbon of ejecta similarly from about S20 near the SW limb seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2024-11-27T02:34Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Not captured in STEREO A COR2 due to overnight data gap which lasted from 2024-12-03T12:23Z to 2024-12-04T00:38Z. Source is likely a small jet-like eruption of material seen on or just beyond the NW limb (W90-W110) and at about N15 in GOES SUVI 304 (seen most clearly at later frame 2024-12-03T20:56Z) immediately following an on-limb filament eruption which had likely resulted in a preceding northwest CME: 2024-12-03T20:36Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Fast CME with protruding/faster nose seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO during a STEREO A COR2 data gap. Likely associated with far-sided activity as evidenced by moving field lines seen off the southeast limb in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A relatively narrow CME associated withthe M6.4 flare from AR 3922 (S18E72), with a narrow southward-deflecting ejecta from this AR seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2024-12-10T04:48Z. Because the sequence of flare/ejecta/CME events is very fast for this and the 2024-12-10T07:24Z CME the attribution to the linked flare is not absolutely certain.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is likely associated with the M1.4 flare from AR 3922 (S18E72) and is also associated with a thin southward-deflecting ejecta from this AR seen in the southwest in GOES SUVI 304 imagery starting at 2024-12-10T07:16Z but best seen after 07:28Z. Because the sequence of flare/ejecta/CME events is very fast for this and the 2024-12-10T07:00Z CME (which is associated to the preceding M5.6 flare from the same active region), the exact attribution to the linked flare for these two CMEs is not absolutely certain.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME associated with M1.5 flare from AR 3922 (S18E72) and a narrow but eventually fan-shaped wide, south-deflecting ejecta from this AR seen in the southeast in SUVI 304/284 and on southeast limb in EUVI A 195 starting at 2024-12-10T11:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Another CME with an asymmetric shape in the "AR 3922 style". It is associated with the M1.9 flare from AR 3922 (S17E55), however the opening of field lines we see in in SUVI 284 seems to be further south from AR 3922. There is also opening of field lines in SUVI 171 closer to this AR.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Far-sided halo CME with brighter bulk seen to the south in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and also a fainter, torus-shaped shock with wider extent in the equatorial regions. Likely associated with far-sided activity as evidenced by expulsion and rapidly flickering field lines as seen off the south limb best in GOES SUVI 284 around 2024-12-11T21:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fast CME to the west, the beginning of which is covered by a data gap in SOHO. Its source was hard to identify since there are multiple eruption close to SW limb near this time, as well as a faint movement of field lines likely beyond the W limb in SUVI 171/195 at 2024-12-15T00:50Z. In EUVI A 195 near the west limb (in STEREO) there are post-eruptive arcades seen at ~2024-12-15T01:05Z after the long data gap. The very approximate location of this  source in STEREO A is ~110 degrees.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright CME with core visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. There is a data gap beginning at 15/11:38Z in STEREO A COR2 imagery for this CME. The CME has a faint halo shock visible in later frames. The source appears to be far sided with wide moving/opening field lines to the SE in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2024-12-15T14:19Z. A portion of the front appears to be moving faster than the rest of the CME which may be indicative of an overlapping CME. However, due to limited stereoscopic viewpoints and lack of a separately identifiable source, this feature was excluded in the measurement of this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME first seen to the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-12-15T20:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 15/11:38Z to 16/00:23Z. The source of this event appears to be an area of field line movement seen along the SE limb (approx. S15E90) as seen in GOES SUVI 195 and 284
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Fast, farsided halo CME in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Not seen in STEREO A COR2 in real time due to a data gap starting at 2024-12-17T11:38Z. Faint, wide field line movement is seen on the southwest limb in GOES SUVI 284 at 2024-12-17T15:59Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Halo CME first seen in STEREO A COR2 at 2024-12-19T17:53Z. The bulk of the CME is to the SW. This CME is also seen in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. This start time was chosen based on when the CME was first seen in available imagery at the time of analysis, but the actual start time is earlier. The source of this CME is most likely far-sided. There are no good source candidates on the Earth-facing disk, and coronal signatures from beyond the SW limb suggest a far-sided source.  In GOES SUVI 284, there is some flickering in the farthest out field lines over the SW limb across most of the SW quadrant first seen at about 2024-12-19T16:19Z. There is also some very faint ejecta seen from beyond the SW limb in GOES SUVI 304 starting about 2024-12-19T16:21Z. Measurements are consistent with a far-sided source. This CME also overlaps with a prior filament eruption to the SW.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The potential source location is near the west limb as seen from GOES SUVI and STEREO A EUV imagery. Opening field lines can be seen in GOES SUVI 284 at 2024-12-21T11:19Z. This can also be faintly seen in STEREO A EUV imagery. Brightening and an ejecta of material can be seen on the west limb in GOES SUVI 304, around S20, possibly near AR 3924, which rotated off of the Earth-facing disk on 2024-12-21.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright loop CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-12-21T20:00Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This event is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning at 2024-12-21T11:39Z. The source of this CME is a filament eruption seen just beyond the NE limb in GOES SUVI 304, along with wide opening field lines seen in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the south in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery and is not observed in STEREO A COR2 due to limited imagery from an ongoing campaign. There is an overlapping CME which appears directed towards the southwest starting around 2024-12-23T11:48Z which may be associated with far-sided activity and is separate from this event. The source is likely associated with the M8.9 flare and subsequent eruption from Active Region 13932 (S18E30) starting around 2024-12-23T11:10Z as seen in GOES SUVI 131, 171, 195, 284, 304 imagery. Ejected material is observed best in GOES SUVI 304 imagery which appears to deflect south of the eruption site. Additionally, dimming is observed south/southwest of the eruption site, centered near S35E20 in GOES SUVI 195 imagery around 2024-12-23T11:15Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the S/SW in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. There is a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery for this event. This CME deflects to the south as it moves out in the field of view. The source appears to be beyond the SW limb in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2024-12-23T19:39Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. STEREO A is in campaign mode during this event with limited to no imagery. The source is an eruption visible to the southwest near S15W70, just east of AR13930 starting around 2024-12-24T05:03Z. There is associated filament ejecta best seen in GOES SUVI 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-12-24T20:24Z. CME also seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C3 and in one frame from STEREO A COR2, which is currently in campaign mode. The source of this CME is likely associated with an M1.0 flare peaking at 20:28Z from AR 3930. The flare and some preceding moving field lines on the SE limb are best seen in GOES SUVI 284 and GOES SUVI 304. There is significant southward deflection. This CME is immediately followed by a slower, more southern CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Relatively faint and very wide CME seen to the south and southeast in SOHO LASCO C2 and to the southeast in STEREO A COR2 during an observing campaign; the CME is associated with an M4.9-class flare and resulting eruption from the vicinity of AR 13932 seen near S18E10 with predominantly southward directionality around 2024-12-25T04:48Z in GOES SUVI 304, 284, 131, and 171. The signature in GOES SUVI 284 is characterized by a destabilizing arcade south of the active region and broad dimming signature. Associated with a type II radio burst with observed shock speed of 1064 km/s.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-12-26T05:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament eruption seen beyond the East limb (approx. S02E100 visually) by GOES SUVI 304 beginning at approximately 26/03:40Z, along with field line movement seen by GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is faintly visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. There is a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery during this event. The source of this CME is a filament eruption visible to the east in GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2024-12-26T17:00Z between S00E70 and S10E80.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is seen to the east in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. There is a data gap in STEREO A COR imagery during this event. The source appears to be a C9.6 flare peaking at 2024-12-26T18:45Z from a currently unnumbered active region near S05E73 based on GOES SUVI 131 imagery. This CME overlaps and overtakes the CME first seen in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2024-12-26T17:48Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

The attached WSA-Enlil+Cone simulation should not be interpreted as a forecast and is likely to overestimate geomagnetic impacts at Earth given that the measurement represents the faint shock associated with the CME, which does not contain much observed material behind the leading edge.

note: Fast partial halo seen generally to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 quickly leaving the SOHO C2 field of view, seemingly associated with an eruption from near the vicinity of Active Region 3939 (S17W58) and associated long duration C7.6-class flare. instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: A narrow faint jet with the likely source a relatively minor eruption centered around ~N17E20, near AR 3947 starting around 2025-01-06T05:08Z in GOES SUVI 304 /195/284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Asymmetrical loop CME seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. This CME is partially obstructed by a data gap in STEREO A COR2 which lasted from 2025-01-07T17:53Z to 2025-01-08T01:38Z. Source is a large eruption and brightening associated with the long-duration M1.1 flare located just beyond SW limb, likely from AR 3939 (S17W99), as seen in GOES SUVI. Widely opening field lines, brightening, and ejection of material can be seen in GOES SUVI 131/171/195/211/304 starting at about 2025-01-07T22:10Z. The tops of post-eruptive arcades can be seen emerging from beyond the SW limb in GOES SUVI 171 starting at about 2025-01-07T23:48Z. There is some uncertainty in the exact location of this eruption since this is not directly on the disk, but it is very likely associated with Active Region 13939 which is estimated to have been located at roughly S17W99 at the peak time of the flare [2025-01-07T23:05Z].
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Diffuse and relatively narrow CME to the N/NW first seen in STEREO A COR2 imagery, then shortly thereafter in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Source is an eruption near the NW limb at N24W80 with narrowly opening field lines and ejecta seen starting at 2025-01-11T07:58Z in GOES SUVI 195/131/171/284 and a small rising loop of filamentary material seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2025-01-11T07:57Z, all wavelengths showing heavy northern deflection. This eruption is associated with a C2.8 flare with peak time 2025-01-11T08:44Z produced by simultaneous brightening from recently-decayed AR 13954 (N24W76) as well as an unnumbered region just beyond the E limb located at an estimated N19E90-N19E100.

This CME overlaps with the CME first seen in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-01-18T02:00Z.

note: Narrow but fast jet in the SW. Source is likely the unnumbered AR ~S20W58, although there are no clearly seen eruptions in EUV imagery at the time.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Fast CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. The source for this CME does not appear to be observed in SDO AIA, GOES SUVI, or STEREO A EUVI, but its direction in both coronagraphs and measurement heavily direct towards a far-sided source around W120-W130. There is a brief filament eruption over the SW limb starting around 2025-01-21T04:38Z in STEREO A EUVI 304, but that is quite early for this signature and that filament is believed to be responsible for CME: 2025-01-21T05:00Z instead.

The curved filament occupied an oval-shaped area on the disk spanning S10-S30 and E38-E65 just prior to eruption. Filamentary material and post eruptive brightening can be seen in SDO AIA 304 at 2025-01-25T00:45Z. Post-eruptive arcades become visible in SDO AIA 171/193/131 around 2025-01-26T02:27Z.

The source of this CME is a distinct set of opening field lines and post-eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 94/171/193 around 2025-01-30T14:25Z located at approx. S15E10, as part of the same filament eruption which sourced CME:2025-01-30T16:12Z, which was seen beginning at approx. 2025-01-30T13:49Z in SDO AIA 304, spanning approx. S05E05 to S40E40.

Eruptive material is also visible over/beyond the southwest limb starting around 2025-02-02T06:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304 imagery. note: CME seen to the SE fully in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and to the S/SW potentially as a partial halo in STEREO COR2A after 2025-02-06T05:09Z, with the CME front already at the edge of its FOV when its beacon data downlink resumes. Due to this data gap timing in STEREO COR2A, the CME is observed in white light imagery but unresolvable in running difference imagery. Observed as a rapid snapping open and dimming of field lines over the SE limb centered ~S28, best observed in SDO AIA 171/193 around 2025-02-06T02:31Z and GOES SUVI 284 around 2025-02-06T02:34Z. Also observed in SDO AIA 304/GOES SUVI 304 as some filament ejecta. The far-sided nature of this CME is also corroborated via fitting in swpc_cat and the lack of an on-disk signature accompanying the field line movement.

Also observed starting around 2025-02-06T10:36Z in SDO AIA 304/GOES SUVI 304, launching more explosively around 2025-02-06T11:32Z. Also seen well as the filament ejecta and field line movement in SDO AIA 171/193.

Coronal signatures include a huge prominence seen directly to the south in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2025-02-12:56Z and originating behind the south limb, and also seen as an extensive movement of matter/field lines to the south and southeast in GOES SUVI 284, also likely happening behind the southern limb. Coronal signatures are almost not seen in SDO AIA, except for minimal movement of ejecta seen in AIA 304.

note: The third in a series of three overlapping CMEs. This bright flux rope CME is visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and to the NW in STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is part of a complex eruption taking place on the NW limb in SDO imagery. Around 2025-02-21T11:27Z, suspended filament material finally ejects outward in SDO AIA 171/193/304. A large post-eruptive arcade on the NW limb also begins around 2025-02-21T11:27Z, expanding from N10->N35 on/just inside the NW limb. This filament eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUVI 195 and 304 imagery, showing post-eruptive arcades and brightening stretching from N35W60 to N15W90, near AR 3989 (~N20W85) [30 degrees have been added to all STEREO A EUVI longitudes to translate to Earth-facing disk coordinates].

note: Very fast and thin CME seen to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 out ahead of the 2025-02-23T03:24Z CME seen to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery; the source is likely associated with an M4.9-class flare from AR 4001 which peaked at 2025-02-23T02:13Z at N25W82 (14001). Beginning around 2025-02-23T02:09Z, wide opening field lines and small post-eruptive arcade are seen in SDO AIA 171/193.

note: Very wide CME seen to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 during a STEREO A COR2A data gap composed with a well-defined western and southwestern leading edge and not-as-defined northern leading edge, associated with an X2.0-class flare and subsequent eruption from AR 14001 (N25W87) as evidenced by strong brightening in SDO AIA 131 and quickly separating field lines seen in SDO AIA 193, 171 and GOES SUVI 284.

note: Bright, wide CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. Source is seen in SDO AIA 171/193/211 as field line movement beginning around 2025-02-24T04:09Z over the NW limb, with an EUV wave at 2025-02-24T15:18Z, and as a filament liftoff starting around 2025-02-24T05:06Z. The source is better seen in STEREO A EUVI with the filament on/just inside the west limb as viewed from STEREO A. At 2025-02-24T05:15Z, STEREO A was located 30.297 degrees from Earth, putting its west limb around W120.3. Here in STEREO A EUVI 304, the filament can be seen slowly rising starting at 2025-02-24T03:15Z->T5:15Z, and ejecting by the next timestamp at T05:45Z. A post-eruptive arcade follows in STEREO A EUVI 195/304. The source could be, or be near, old AR 3989, which rotated off the west limb on 2025-02-21 and would be located approximately W115-W125.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is first seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3, but not in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning at 2025-02-24T20:23Z. The source of this CME is likely associated with an eruption visible beyond the SW limb starting around 2025-02-24T20:27Z as seen in SDO/AIA 131 with associated brightening, moving/opening field lines, and an EUV wave best seen in SDO/AIA 211. Following the eruption, there were very notably post-eruptive arcades which were associated with a long duration, occulted M3.9 flare from former AR 13990 (S13W120) that peaked at 2024-02-24T23:02Z. The very beginning of the flare can be seen in STEREO A EUVI 195 on the W limb in the last frame (2025-02-24T20:35Z) prior to the end of a downlink period. Additionally, very fast opening field lines are visible from beyond the W limb starting around 2025-02-24T20:24Z in SDO/AIA 193, SDO/AIA 171, GOES SUVI 195, and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen in the West by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-26T06:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2. The source of this event is a filament eruption centered at approx. S10W25 exhibiting a strong Westward deflection. This filament is visible in SDO AIA and STEREO A EUVI 304, along with dimming and post eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 94, 193 and STEREO A EUVI 195. A large North-South configured coronal hole is visible approximately 10 degrees to the East of the eruptive source. This coronal hole may cause deflection or acceleration of this CME.

The possible source of this CME is a filament eruption beginning around 2025-02-26T11:15Z in STEREO A EUVI, GOES SUVI, and SDO/AIA 304 imagery near ~S15W90+. A slow rising loop is visible in GOES SUVI 304 and 284 imagery along the W/SW limb starting around 2025-02-26T12:00Z which may have been fully released from the lower/middle corona when the filament eruption associated with the overlapping CME to the SW occurred.

note: Bright, partial halo to halo CME visible in the W/NW of SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. Post eruptive arcades are also visible in STEREO A EUVI 304 and 195 starting around 2025-02-28T17:35Z. Moving/opening field lines and an EUV wave is visible in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2025-02-28T17:00Z. The source is suspected to be from AR 13993 (~N15W125) based on available STEREO A EUVI data. Note that there was a simultaneous, much less significant, eruption centered at (~W01W60) at the time of the far-sided eruption associated with this CME.

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

Note that there also seems to be an even more minor eruption off the SW limb at the same time seen in SDO AIA 304/ GOES SUVI 304.
