note: Faint CME visible to the S/SE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The potential source of this CME is a filament eruption centered near S27E45 (below active regions 14012 and 14011) starting around 2025-03-04T03:20Z as seen in SDO/AIA 304. Associated moving/opening field lines and possible EUV wave visible to the south and south west towards the south pole as seen in SDO/AIA 193 indicating southern deflection, likely due to the coronal hole located N/NE of the source location. Associated brightening and dimming are also visible in SDO/AIA 131, 304, and 193 in the area of the source with additional dimming visible further south closer to the south pole.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. This CME partially overlaps the CME first seen in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-03-04T03:48Z. The potential source for this CME is a filament eruption near S42W95 with associated moving/opening field lines visible along the SW limb in SDO/AIA 304 and 171 starting around 2025-03-04T03:51Z. There appears to be southward deflection possibly due to coronal holes in the vicinity of the source location. The coronal holes and the eruptions deflection are more clearly seen in STEREO A EUVI 195 and 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This event is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. The source is likely an eruption visible on/near the southwest limb starting around 2025-03-04T18:30Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the west/northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. It is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2025-03-04T19:38Z. The source is likely related to an eruption visible near the northwest limb (centered near ~N15W80) starting around 2025-03-04T21:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This narrow on-disk CME is seen as a faint flux rope due south in SOHO LASCO C2 and simultaneously as a faint loop to the southeast in STEREO A COR2, which is currently 30 degrees to the west of SOHO LASCO. The source is a subtle eruption from AR 4012 (S20W00) starting at 2025-03-07T21:35Z, seen as dimming, brightening, and field line opening in SDO AIA 193 and 171, as well as GOES SUVI 284 and 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow and fast CME seen to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery associated with a point source eruption from Active Region 14011 (S14W29) seen erupting around 2025-03-08T14:45Z in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 284. The active region footpoint is seen to have a small brightening during the eruption followed by a dark jet of plasma material leaving to the southwest with some deflection to the west.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint and relatively narrow CME to the southwest in STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. The leading edge appears slightly brighter in STEREO A COR2 than in SOHO LASCO. The source is opening field lines seen starting at 2025-03-11T03:35Z located on or just beyond the W limb as seen in STEREO A EUVI 195 (W120-130 from SDO AIA perspective) and spanning approximately N00 to S10 in latitude, although the eruption likely extends to farther beyond the limb. Field line movement and the disappearance of a small loop of material can be seen from the same location in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery between the 2025-03-11T03:45Z and 2025-03-11T04:45Z frames.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Super narrow jet (with the 2 degree half-width or so), seen only in SOHO LASCO C2 and faintly in a few early timestamps of C3. Not discernible in STEREO A COR2, likely because of its faintness. Likely associated with the M1.1 flare from AR 14024 (N5W47).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: One of two overlapping loop CMEs visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2. The source is additional wide and subtle field line movement seen on and very likely extending beyond the SW limb, best seen in STEREO A EUVI 193, and likely a direct consequence of or sympathetic eruption to a filament eruption seen starting at to lift off the southwest limb at 2025-03-15T04:09Z as seen in SDO AIA 304, 193, and 171. This CME heavily overlaps with CME: 2025-03-15T05:36Z, whose source is the filament eruption on the southwest limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note:
One of two overlapping loop CMEs visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2. The source is a filament eruption on the southwest limb, spanning from about S25W85 to S10W120 with southward deflection seen as it erupts in SDO AIA and STEREO-A EUV imagery. This CME heavily overlaps with CME: 2025-03-15T05:24Z, whose source is nearly simultaneous and in close proximity. 

Filamentary material is seen starting to lift off at 2025-03-15T04:09Z in SDO AIA 304, 193, and 171. Post-eruptive arcades can be seen in SDO AIA 193 and 171 starting at 2025-03-15T06:28Z and lasting for multiple hours. Bright material can be seen in GOES SUVI 304 as well. This eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUVI 304 and 193 imagery, which has frames available after a data gap ending at 2025-03-15T03:45Z and reveals liftoff of material starting with the next frame with timestamp 2025-03-15T04:15Z. With STEREO A currently at a HEEQ longitude of 31, this vantage point reveals that there was a filament eruption and a separate but sympathetic rising loop directly next to the filament, which altogether extended from approximately S25W80 to S10W121 (coordinates listed as would be seen by SDO. STEREO A is currently at a HEEQ longitude of +31 degrees).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Complex-shaped, somewhat pointy-nosed and possibly partial halo CME to the southwest, seen the brightest in STEREO A COR2. Its source is behind the SW limb (both in SDO and in STEREO A) and likely associated with Active Region 4012 (now at approximately W125) which was fairly complex when it was on the Earth-facing disk; its coronal signatures are fast-opening field lines behind the SW limb in both EUV imagers starting at 2025-03-16T00:32Z, as seen in SDO AIA 193/171, EUVI A 195 and SUVI 285. Much later (after 05Z) some high post-eruptive arcades are seen in EUVI A 304 appearing from behind the limb, indicating the source that is far behind the limb, as seen from STEREO A. The much fainter shock can be best seen mostly as it pushes the streamer in the south south west towards the east. Likely deflection of about 10 to 20 degrees eastward relative to the source at W125 caused by a large coronal hole located to the northwest of Active Region 4012.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-18T08:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament eruption seen at approx. S30E65 in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304. Field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171 and 193, along with post eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 94, 131 and 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is faintly visible to the E/NE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. It is not clearly seen in STEREO A COR2 data due to a data gap from 2025-03-18T15:39Z to 2025-03-19T03:09Z. The source appears to be a filament eruption beyond the E/NE limb starting around 2025-03-19T00:30Z as seen in SDO/AIA 131, 171, 193, and 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint but fast CME with an asymmetrical front, with a protruding nose to the south, seen directed to the west in SOHO with the start covered by the nighttime data gap in SOHO. Its source is the filament eruption seen on/behind the SW limb: as ejecta/prominence in AIA 304 (there are actually two ejectas - a more southern complex shaped loop-like prominence seen at 2025-03-19T22:50Z at latitude of -21, and a fan-shaped ejecta to the north of it seen at latitude of -7 at 2025-03-19T223:46Z. This eruption is also seen as fast opening of field lines behind the limb in AIA 193/171 starting at 2025-03-19T222:01Z and later (starting at 2025-03-19T223:21Z) as bright post-eruptive arcades on/behind the limb in AIA 131. There is an associated long duration occulted C6.0 flare peaking at 2025-03-20T00:07Z from behind the limb (bright arcades). It is possible that the flare is from former Active Region 4018 (S21W100).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Loop CME with brighter, narrower bulk and fainter shock visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 during a STEREO A COR2 data gap. The source of the CME appears to the ejection of material from near the vicinity of Active Region 4022 just near N08W75, first distinctly seen as a distinct instance of opening field lines and brightening starting around 2025-03-20T17:24Z in SDO AIA 193 and 304 imagery. Faint flickering field lines far off the western limb seen in GOES SUVI 284 suggest that a component of this large scale eruption may be far-sided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint halo CME with a bulk visible mainly to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery (more easily seen in difference imagery). There is no STEREO A COR2 imagery for this event due to a data gap. The source of this CME appears to be a large dimming region centered near N02E07 starting around 2025-03-21T15:49Z with a southeast directionality based on the minor EUV wave visible in SDO/AIA 211 and 193 imagery. There's a large coronal hole situated E/SE of the dimming region and a separate coronal hole due west of the dimming region which may have contributed to the deflection visible on the solar disk in SDO/AIA imagery. This source location appears to be a sympathetic eruption to the M1.2 flare from AR14028 (S17W33) seen to the SW in SDO/AIA 131 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the north/northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. The source is likely related to an eruption centered near N28E45 starting around 2025-03-22T13:45Z which exhibits northern deflection as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is faint but visible as a partial halo directed towards the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. It is observed as a faint far-sided halo in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided, and may be related to faint field line movement visible far beyond the southeast limb in GOES SUVI 284 imagery starting around 2025-03-22T14:35Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This narrow CME is visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. It is not clearly seen in STEREO A COR2 imagery due to an ongoing campaign. The source appears to be filament ejecta with associated field line movement to the SE in SDO/AIA 171, 193, and 304 starting around 2025-03-24T15:22Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME seen to the SE in STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C3. Source is field line opening seen just beyond the SE limb at a latitude of about S16 and an approximated longitude of about E90 to E110 in SDO AIA 193 beginning at 2025-03-25T14:49Z. Analysis of this CME was affected by a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery lasting from 2025-03-25T13:42Z to 2025-03-25T17:30Z, reduced image quality of SOHO LASCO C3 frames for timestamps following 2025-03-25T17:30Z, and by the regular overnight data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery which began at 2025-03-25T15:53Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is a filament eruption centered around S20E30. Filament liftoff starts around 2025-03-27T20:19Z in SDO AIA 304. Dimming is best seen in SDO AIA 193, and opening field lines are best seen in SDO AIA 171/193. The eruption is also visible from the point of view of STEREO A EUV 195/304 imagery. The main bulk of the CME is preceded by a fainter, narrower loop in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-03-27T21:36Z that may be associated with an eruption from the same region, around S20E30.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This event is visible to the east/northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. This CME is still developing and only early imagery is available as a result. The source is related to an eruption and X1.1 flare from Active Region 14046 starting around 2025-03-28T15:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. A subsequent wide opening of field lines can be observed in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery at this time as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Jet-like CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-29T23:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 29/16:53Z to 30/03:38Z. The source of this event is an M1.9 flare from Active Region 4048 (S15E85) seen in SDO AIA 94 and 131. Field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2; it is partially obscured by the pylon in C3, but its western edge is seen in SOHO LASCO C3. The source of it is likely an eruption with a very minor ejecta seen in SDO AIA 304/131/193 and GOES SUVI 284 at 2025-03-30T04:07Z just southwest of AR 4048 (S20E70) as post-eruptive arcades and small area dimming. The associated flare is a C3.5 flare observed in GOES-S, not in GOES-P, due to an eclipse.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME (somewhat brighter in STEREO COR2 coronagraph than in SOHO LASCO), seen to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Its source is a filament/ejecta on/close to the northwest limb, seen erupting starting at 2025-03-30T07:48Z in SDO AIA 171/403/131 and GOES SUVI 284/304, and seen as an opening of field lines and later as post-eruptive arcades/brightening in SDO AIA 193 extending to ~N22W70 but possibly centered around the northwest limb or even beyond the limb. The eruption is well seen in STEREO A EUV imagery happening to the east of AR 4035 (N16W94) and centered around ~N22W90.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint loop CME seen to the S in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, SE in STEREO A COR2. Source is an eruption seen starting at 2025-04-03T03:24Z from AR 4045 (S15W05) with Eastern deflection. Brightening and ejecta seen deflected to the east as seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2025-04-03T03:24Z. SDO AIA imagery was in a data gap which lasted from 2025-04-02T15:52Z to 2025-04-03T04:54Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the E/SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. There is no STEREO A COR2 imagery available for this event due to a data gap beginning at 2025-04-03T15:23Z. The source is a filament eruption visible along the SE limb in GOES SUVI 304 near S25E70 starting around 2025-03-04T17:32Z. Additionally moving/opening field lines are visible in GOES SUVI 171, 195, and 284, as well as brightening which is best seen in GOES SUVI 195. There is a data gap in SDO/AIA during the eruption for this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME seen to the N in SOHO LASCO C2 and to the N in STEREO A COR2. Source is a filament eruption from just beyond the NW limb. A prominence from just beyond the limb can be seen beginning to liftoff starting at 2025-04-04T16:08Z in GOES SUVI 304. Opening field lines seen in GOES SUVI 284 and ejecta seen in GOES SUVI 304 both show strong northern deflection of this eruption, with ejecta traveling nearly due north. STEREO A EUVI 195 and 304 show that the prominence was centered at about N30 and spanned from W82-W92 (in SDO coordinates).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fast loop CME seen to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and to the east-southeast in STEREO A COR2, quickly leaving the SOHO LASCO C2 field of view and comprised of a faint, asymmetric shock seen to the northeast. The likely source is an eruption seen near the vicinity of Active Region 4057 near N10E55 to E65 (after deflection), characterized by a brightening near the footpoints and a subsequent ejection of magnetic field flux seen occurring to the east starting around 2025-04-08T05:45Z, best in SDO AIA 171 and SDO AIA 304. The eruption is also seen, though not as strongly in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284. Also associated with a type II radio burst with begin time 05:53Z and velocity 456 km/s.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME seen to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and to the east-southeast in STEREO A COR2, quickly leaving the SOHO LASCO C2 field of view. The likely source is a secondary eruption seen near the vicinity of Active Region 4057 near N10E55 to E65 (after deflection) following CME: 2025-04-08T06:00Z characterized by a brightening near the footpoints and a subsequent ejection of plasma seen occurring to the east starting around 2025-04-08T08:00Z, best in SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very faint narrow but fast jet to the northeast in both coronagraphs. Its source could be a narrow filament eruption off the northeast limb seen in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304 at ~2025-04-09T06:39Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint and narrow jet CME visible to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. No STEREO A COR2 imagery was available in real time for this CME due to a data gap which began at 2025-04-09T18:53Z. There was no clear source for this CME; there are several small instances of field line movement in the Western hemisphere of the disk and on the West limb, but none distinct enough to consider as a candidate source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Extremely faint and narrow CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2. The leading edge becomes diffuse before leaving the C2 field of view. Source is unclear, but there is continual flickering and field line movement from AR 4055 (N08W43), including a small instance of southward directed field line movement seen starting at 2025-04-11T12:45Z in SDO AIA 171. No STEREO A COR2 imagery was available in real time for this CME due to a data gap which began at 2025-04-11T11:23Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Wide loop CME visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2. Source is an eruption near the NE limb, seen as a rising loop of opening field lines starting at 2025-04-11T20:40Z in SDO AIA 171. There are two connected rising loops seen on the E limb, which lift off together in the same eruption. One spans from approx. N22 to N30 along E70, while the other spans from approx. N35 to N50 along E90. No STEREO A COR2 imagery was available in real time for this CME due to a data gap which began at 2025-04-11T11:23Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: A bright, relatively narrow high southern latitude CME along a streamer to SSW in both coronagraphs.  The CME source is the wide opening/movement of field lines on/behind southwest limb starting ~2025-04-14T14:24Z, as seen in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284/304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely associated with an eruption and opening of field lines visible near or slightly beyond the eastern limb in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery starting around 2025-04-15T14:30Z. Additionally, post-eruptive arcades begin to form around 2025-04-15T17:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Jet CME that appears to look like CME: 2025-04-17T09:12Z seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2; the CME likely originates from the far-side or just beyond the northeast limb as seen by a fast moving jet of plasma in SDO AIA 304 / GOES SUVI 304 imagery around 2025-04-17T11:37Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Very narrow (with <10 deg half-width), faint, fast jet to the northeast in both coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2) mostly seen in running difference imagery (almost not noticeable in white light images). Possible coronal signature (for this likely backsided event) could be minor post-eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 304 peaking from behind the NE limb after 2025-04-17T14Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-04-19T00:00Z. Also seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C3 but is partially obscured by the pylon. The start of the CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting from 2025-04-18T22:38Z to 2025-04-19T02:38Z, and following the data gap the leading edge is out of the field of view. This CME is associated with an M4.4 flare peaking at 2025-04-18T23:50Z and ejecta from on/beyond the SE limb (~S29E90). A Type II radio burst was also observed. The flare and associated ejecta are seen across SDO AIA and GOES SUVI wavelengths but are most clearly seen in SDO AIA 304 and SDO AIA 131. A wider, possible shock front is visible in a few early frames of SOHO LASCO C2, but quickly fades away and was determined to not be measurable. The CME experiences continued southward deflection through propagation.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Two heavily overlapping flux rope CMEs from the same source seen to the south in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is two instances of significant dimming and opening field lines seen from the same location, AR 4065 (S31E10), starting at 2025-04-22T06:37Z then at 2025-04-22T07:24Z. There appears to be southern deflection in the UV imagery. Post eruptive brightening can be seen in SDO AIA 193 starting at 2025-04-22T08:13Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. It has a bright core that fills more to the right side of the CME with a more faint leading edge. The source is an eruption from AR 14060 (N08W90) on/just beyond the western limb associated with an M1.3 flare, filament ejecta, and post-eruptive arcades as best seen in GOES SUVI 131, 304, and 171. This source is also visible in STEREO A EUVI 304 and SDO/AIA imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the South in SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-04-24T14:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a Southern deflected eruption from AR 4065 (S31W22) beginning at approx. 24/13:34Z. This eruption and subsequent Southern dimming can be seen in SDO AIA 171, 193 and 211. This deflection is likely due to the Active Region's proximity to a large positive polarity coronal hole.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint and narrow CME to the E in SOHO LASCO C2 and E in STEREO A COR2. Source is a small eruption from AR 14075 at S11E43 seen starting as early as 2025-04-26T09:57Z. Brightening and a small amount of ejecta can be seen in SDO AIA 304. Brightening and field line movement can be seen in SDO AIA 193, 171. Ejecta can be seen in STEREO A EUVI 304 at timestamp 2025-04-26T10:15Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fast jet CME seen to the SW in STEREO A COR2 during a SOHO C2/C3 data gap likely in excess of 1000 km/s. The source at first glimpse and with higher confidence appears to be an eruption just beyond the western limb as seen mostly by quickly darkening field lines off the southwest limb in SDO AIA 171 around 2025-04-29T14:00Z, but with low confidence may be associated with Active Region 4070 (S12W51) as some minor darkening in the active region seen best in GOES SUVI 284 around 2025-04-29T14:00Z. Measurement will be created assuming the limb-related source.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-04-29T23:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap which began at 2025-04-29T19:23Z. The source of this event is a C7.3 flare from AR 4065 (S31W91) and subsequent filament eruption as seen exhibiting Southern deflection in SDO AIA 131, 304 and GOES SUVI 304. Wide opening field lines are also visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

A significant area of opening field lines and dimming can be seen from near AR 14100 (N12E12) in SDO AIA 193/171/131/304 and GOES SUVI 284/304 beginning at 2025-05-30T23:47Z, immediately after the flare. It appears that most of the filamentary material ejected is from the upper lobe of the '3', and departs from approximately N10W15.

note: Faint CME first seen in the SE by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-06-24T16:09Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is a minor eruption from the vicinity of Active Region 14117 (S15W05) exhibiting a Southeastern deflection as seen in SDO AIA 94, 171 and 193. This deflection is likely due to a large negative polarity coronal hole situated just Northwest of this eruption, causing a Southeastern deflection away from central meridian.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Narrow CME seen to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2. Source is uncertain, but possibly this small filament seen disappearing in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery at about 2025-06-24T17:45Z, located at about N00W110. Faint field line movement is also visible beyond the STEREO A EUVI western limb around this time, so the source may be an eruption further beyond the limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: An extremely faint narrow CME/jet, the front of which is seen in difference imagery of SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 in a couple of timestamps (after which it dissipates) and not seen in SOHO LASCO C3. It is likely well out of ecliptic. No clear source was found, however there is possibly a very minor opening/movement of field lines to the NW in AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284 around that time, but the source is unclear.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-06-25T06:36Z. Also seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. There is some minor northward deflection into the FOV of SOHO LASCO C3. This CME will likely combine with the earlier, slower CME: 2025-05-24T23:48Z. The source of this CME is most likely from beyond the W limb. There is some minor field line movement visible over the W limb in SDO AIA 193 starting around 2025-05-25T06:00Z

This front is preceeded by a faint, too diffuse to track outflow beginning at 2025-07-07T13:36Z in LASCO C2.
